Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.38,0:00:04.32,Default,,0,0,0,,This month I’d like to talk about the efforts \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.32,0:00:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s organization is making \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.32,0:00:09.73,Default,,0,0,0,,to produce literature, publications, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.73,0:00:13.90,Default,,0,0,0,,articles that are as accurate as possible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.90,0:00:18.90,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to talk about accuracy\N—accuracy of statement. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.90,0:00:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, first, what’s the responsibility \Nof the writer of the article? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.54,0:00:27.58,Default,,0,0,0,,When a writer submits \Nan article for publication, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.58,0:00:32.25,Default,,0,0,0,,he is expected to supply references \Nfrom reputable sources \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.25,0:00:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,to back up the facts \Nthat he’s included in his article. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.02,0:00:37.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And our Research Department \Nwill use those references \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.79,0:00:40.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to check the accuracy of everything.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.72,0:00:44.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Reliable, respected sources. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.13,0:00:47.56,Default,,0,0,0,,What do we mean by a reliable source? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.56,0:00:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, first of all, we go with encyclopedias, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.87,0:00:55.87,Default,,0,0,0,,books, magazines, and then newspapers\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.87,0:00:58.01,Default,,0,0,0,,—basically in that order. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.01,0:01:01.28,Default,,0,0,0,,We prefer encyclopedias over books, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.28,0:01:03.88,Default,,0,0,0,,books over magazines, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.88,0:01:05.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and magazines over newspapers\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.92,0:01:09.49,Default,,0,0,0,,—generally because newspaper editors \Nhave a hard time checking their facts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.49,0:01:13.42,Default,,0,0,0,,They have a very limited time \Nin which to check their facts. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.42,0:01:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Even encyclopedias and books get updated, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.23,0:01:20.63,Default,,0,0,0,,so we have to go \Nwith the latest edition of those. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.63,0:01:24.63,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to make sure \Nthat our sources are reliable.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.63,0:01:27.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, when a writer quotes an expert, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.70,0:01:31.31,Default,,0,0,0,,our researchers will ask: \N“Who’s this expert? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.31,0:01:33.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“What’s his reputation? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.31,0:01:36.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“Is he working for a particular organization? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.51,0:01:39.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“Does this organization have an agenda? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.75,0:01:41.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it a special-interest group?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.95,0:01:46.02,Default,,0,0,0,,If we find that the goals \Nof the organization are questionable, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.02,0:01:51.59,Default,,0,0,0,,we won’t use the quote\N—even if it’s a really good quote.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.59,0:01:55.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, suppose that a writer \Nwants to quote something from a book. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.70,0:01:57.73,Default,,0,0,0,,In the reference material, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.73,0:02:00.94,Default,,0,0,0,,he’ll supply a photocopy \Nof the quote in the book, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.94,0:02:04.94,Default,,0,0,0,,but very often he’ll give us \Ntwo or three pages before the quote \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.94,0:02:07.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and two or three pages after as well. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.84,0:02:11.05,Default,,0,0,0,,And that way, \Nour researchers can examine the quote \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.05,0:02:15.15,Default,,0,0,0,,in context to make sure \Nthat what we’re saying in print \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.15,0:02:18.86,Default,,0,0,0,,is really what the author \Nof the quote had in mind.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.86,0:02:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, \Nan evolutionist might make a statement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.16,0:02:24.16,Default,,0,0,0,,which on the surface \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.16,0:02:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,appears to confirm his support of creation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.83,0:02:30.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps an atheist will make a statement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.10,0:02:33.60,Default,,0,0,0,,that seems to indicate \Nthat he believes in God. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.60,0:02:36.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But when you examine \Nthe quote in context, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.01,0:02:39.98,Default,,0,0,0,,you realize that that isn’t what \Nthe author had in mind at all. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.98,0:02:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,We would never \Ndeliberately distort a quotation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.25,0:02:49.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We try very hard to use all \Nof our quotations in context.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.05,0:02:53.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, it’s important to keep up \Nwith the very latest research. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.72,0:02:58.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Something that was stated years ago \Nas a fact may have been disproved. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.36,0:03:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And the reason why is obvious. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.40,0:03:02.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Someone may spend his entire life \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.57,0:03:06.40,Default,,0,0,0,,researching a very limited point in history\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.40,0:03:08.40,Default,,0,0,0,,—a very small point in history—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.40,0:03:10.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and, of course, \Nif he spends so much time researching, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.61,0:03:12.61,Default,,0,0,0,,he’s going to uncover things. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.61,0:03:15.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And so it’s not surprising \Nthat from time to time \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.11,0:03:19.25,Default,,0,0,0,,we have to adjust our view \Nof some historical points. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.25,0:03:21.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to check, check, check. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.75,0:03:26.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And later on in this discussion, \Nwe’re going to consider some examples of it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.02,0:03:28.73,Default,,0,0,0,,It’ll be fun; you’ll love it!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.73,0:03:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, someone might ask, \N‘Why is it necessary to be so picky, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.00,0:03:36.73,Default,,0,0,0,,to be so fussy, about accuracy?’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.73,0:03:39.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And in answer, \NI’d like to give an experience \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.97,0:03:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that I heard about a few years ago. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.14,0:03:44.31,Default,,0,0,0,,In Northern Europe, \Nthere was a man \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.31,0:03:47.38,Default,,0,0,0,,who accepted a Bible study \Nfrom Jehovah’s Witnesses. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.38,0:03:49.38,Default,,0,0,0,,And when he was asked \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.38,0:03:52.18,Default,,0,0,0,,what motivated him \Nto want to study, he said: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.18,0:03:55.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“I read an article \Nin your Awake! magazine on trees. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.85,0:03:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now, I happen to be \Na bit of an expert on trees. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.09,0:04:02.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“And after I read the article, \NI said to myself: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.36,0:04:05.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘That article was so well-documented. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.63,0:04:07.73,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘It was so precise. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.73,0:04:11.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Any organization that is that careful \Nwhen writing about trees \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.94,0:04:15.44,Default,,0,0,0,,is going to be just as careful \Nwhen teaching me the Bible.’” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.44,0:04:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And on that basis, \Nhe accepted a Bible study.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.54,0:04:23.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, an area where great care \Nneeds to be taken \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.81,0:04:26.18,Default,,0,0,0,,is when we’re quoting statistics. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.18,0:04:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,A newspaper may report on a disaster \Nin a certain country \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.52,0:04:34.29,Default,,0,0,0,,and say that 10,000 people \Nwere killed in the disaster. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.29,0:04:37.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Immediately, \Nour researchers are going to ask, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.23,0:04:39.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“Where did they get that statistic?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.66,0:04:42.70,Default,,0,0,0,,They might phone the newspaper \Nand ask for the source. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.70,0:04:45.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And if the reporter \Ncan’t confirm the statistic, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.70,0:04:48.71,Default,,0,0,0,,our researchers will go to another source\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.71,0:04:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—a more official source—\Nto get the correct statistic.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.51,0:04:57.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Care is also taken \Nwhen quoting personalities of the past. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.41,0:05:02.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, suppose we want to quote \Nsomething that Napoleon Bonaparte said\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.32,0:05:04.32,Default,,0,0,0,,—the French general. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.32,0:05:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, being French, \NNapoleon spoke French. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.99,0:05:09.99,Default,,0,0,0,,So if we’re quoting it in English, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.99,0:05:14.66,Default,,0,0,0,,that means that somebody translated \Nthe quote from French into English. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.66,0:05:18.47,Default,,0,0,0,,But did they translate the quote correctly? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.47,0:05:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Our researchers will probably go \Nto the target language \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.67,0:05:27.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and research the quote \Nin French or in another language. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.21,0:05:32.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And more often than not, \Nthey find that what is presented in English \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.18,0:05:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,doesn’t accurately represent \Nwhat the individual said at all.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.72,0:05:41.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, as we age, \Nour memory can play tricks on us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.36,0:05:44.83,Default,,0,0,0,,And our researchers are aware of that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.83,0:05:47.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Suppose that an elderly brother \Nwrites in his life story \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.66,0:05:52.44,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was baptized \Nat a circuit assembly on a certain date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.44,0:05:55.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Our researchers may look at the date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.30,0:05:57.31,Default,,0,0,0,,They may check the date, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.31,0:06:01.54,Default,,0,0,0,,and suppose they find that the date \Nthe brother gave fell on a Tuesday. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.54,0:06:06.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what are the chances that there was \Na circuit assembly on a Tuesday? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.08,0:06:08.82,Default,,0,0,0,,There may have been, \Nbut they’re going to check. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.82,0:06:11.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Is the brother’s memory failing him? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.82,0:06:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,If they can’t confirm the date, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.86,0:06:16.09,Default,,0,0,0,,they may ask someone to help the brother \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.09,0:06:19.26,Default,,0,0,0,,to remember the date \Nmore correctly, more accurately. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.26,0:06:23.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps someone was baptized \Nat the same circuit assembly as he was, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.20,0:06:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and perhaps that person \Nhas an accurate note of the date.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.14,0:06:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Our translators also go to great lengths \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.04,0:06:35.48,Default,,0,0,0,,to present accurate information \Nto the brothers and sisters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.48,0:06:38.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Some time ago, \Nthe Awake! magazine published an article \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.28,0:06:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,on a very rare species of butterfly. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.68,0:06:44.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, with all animals and insects, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.45,0:06:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,we provide our translators \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.72,0:06:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,with the Latin name \Nof the animal or the insect. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.83,0:06:52.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And so our translators had the Latin name. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.20,0:06:54.20,Default,,0,0,0,,But in one large country, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.20,0:06:57.13,Default,,0,0,0,,they were unable to find \Nthe name in the vernacular. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.13,0:06:59.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what did they do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.14,0:07:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,They phoned the country’s leading university, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.37,0:07:05.37,Default,,0,0,0,,and they were transferred \Nto the Biology Department, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.37,0:07:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and there an expert gave them \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.44,0:07:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,the name in the vernacular \Nof that particular butterfly. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.31,0:07:14.62,Default,,0,0,0,,But then he said: \N“Why is it that you’re worrying so much \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.62,0:07:16.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“about the correct name of this butterfly? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.85,0:07:19.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“If you got it wrong, \Nthere are only two of us \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.32,0:07:22.23,Default,,0,0,0,,in the whole country \Nwho would’ve known the difference.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.23,0:07:27.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that opened the way \Nto give a witness to this expert.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.66,0:07:29.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, now, how well would you do \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.67,0:07:32.34,Default,,0,0,0,,in spotting a statement that is slightly off \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.34,0:07:34.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and making it more accurate? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.60,0:07:36.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Would you like to find out? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.61,0:07:39.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course you would! \NIt’ll be fun. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.11,0:07:41.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So let’s take a quiz that I’ll call \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.31,0:07:43.41,Default,,0,0,0,,You Be the Editor. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.41,0:07:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to put \Na number of statements on the screen, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.35,0:07:48.99,Default,,0,0,0,,and there’s a problem \Nwith each one of them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.99,0:07:51.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Now your job \Nis to figure out what’s wrong, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.99,0:07:55.99,Default,,0,0,0,,why it is wrong, \Nand then suggest how to fix it. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.99,0:07:57.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s going to be fun.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.99,0:08:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s the first statement: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.00,0:08:04.07,Default,,0,0,0,,“According \Nto the Smithsonian Knowledge Encyclopedia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.07,0:08:06.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“the Egyptian Sphinx \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.10,0:08:10.47,Default,,0,0,0,,was constructed around 2550 B.C.E.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.47,0:08:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,“The Egyptian Sphinx \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.11,0:08:17.45,Default,,0,0,0,,was constructed around 2550 B.C.E.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.45,0:08:19.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the problem \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.48,0:08:21.95,Default,,0,0,0,,is with the date 2550 B.C.E. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.95,0:08:23.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The global Flood occurred \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.95,0:08:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,about 200 years after that date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.86,0:08:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what are the chances \Nthat the Sphinx survived the Flood? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.29,0:08:35.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Unless, of course, you think \Nthat’s how the Sphinx lost his nose. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.30,0:08:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, these dates \Nare good for you school children \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.40,0:08:40.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to keep in mind \Nwhen you’re writing reports. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.50,0:08:43.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes you copy something \Nfrom an encyclopedia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.07,0:08:45.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and it gives a certain date. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.07,0:08:48.41,Default,,0,0,0,,But think about the date of the Flood,\N2370 B.C.E.,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.41,0:08:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,so that what you put in your report \Nis as accurate as possible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.85,0:08:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s go on to the next one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.49,0:08:59.49,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 29 C.E., \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.49,0:09:03.06,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jesus was baptized by a close relative, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.06,0:09:06.66,Default,,0,0,0,,John the Baptizer.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.66,0:09:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, 29 C.E., that looks right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.20,0:09:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And we know that Jesus \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.20,0:09:13.37,Default,,0,0,0,,was baptized by John; that’s right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.37,0:09:15.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So the problem must be \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.40,0:09:18.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“close relative,” and it is. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.51,0:09:20.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, both of Jesus’ parents \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.88,0:09:25.58,Default,,0,0,0,,were of the tribe of Judah, \Nand their parents were of the tribe of Judah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.58,0:09:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,But, what about John’s parents, \NZechariah and Elizabeth? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.25,0:09:31.45,Default,,0,0,0,,They were both of the tribe of Levi. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:31.45,0:09:34.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So Elizabeth and Mary \Ncouldn’t have been sisters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.12,0:09:36.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Could they have been cousins? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.16,0:09:37.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.26,0:09:39.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We can’t even confirm that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.26,0:09:43.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And if they were, that would make \NJesus and John second cousins. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.43,0:09:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, is a second cousin a “close relative”? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.70,0:09:49.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Some would say yes; \Nsome would say no. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.27,0:09:51.84,Default,,0,0,0,,So it’s safer just to say, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.84,0:09:56.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 29 C.E., \NJesus was baptized by a relative, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.15,0:09:58.85,Default,,0,0,0,,John the Baptizer.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.85,0:09:59.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.95,0:10:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s see if you can spot \Nthe error in this one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.72,0:10:04.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“While most of the early Christians \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.72,0:10:07.49,Default,,0,0,0,,“were held in little esteem in the community, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.49,0:10:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“a few enjoyed an elevated social status. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.89,0:10:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, Luke was a respected physician.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.43,0:10:18.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the word we need \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.10,0:10:20.80,Default,,0,0,0,,to look at is “respected.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.80,0:10:23.54,Default,,0,0,0,,We respect our doctors today, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.54,0:10:26.94,Default,,0,0,0,,and our doctors have \Na very, very fine education. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.94,0:10:29.78,Default,,0,0,0,,But was that the case in the first century? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.78,0:10:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,A reference work says this \Nabout first-century physicians: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.25,0:10:37.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“Many doctors were freed Greek slaves, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.75,0:10:42.26,Default,,0,0,0,,“hence the social standing \Nof doctors was quite low. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.26,0:10:45.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“Because recovery rates were so low, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.16,0:10:48.93,Default,,0,0,0,,many people were skeptical \Nor even scornful of doctors.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.93,0:10:51.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Note this statement from the first century: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.80,0:10:55.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“Until recently, Diaulus was a doctor; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.40,0:10:58.24,Default,,0,0,0,,“now he is an undertaker. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.24,0:11:00.51,Default,,0,0,0,,“He is still doing as an undertaker, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.51,0:11:03.51,Default,,0,0,0,,what he used to do as a doctor.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.51,0:11:05.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Not very flattering, is it? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.51,0:11:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, in this case, we’d probably have to use \Na different example.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.75,0:11:11.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.29,0:11:14.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 325 C.E., \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.36,0:11:16.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“the Roman Emperor Constantine \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.36,0:11:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“established Christianity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.39,0:11:20.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“as the official religion \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.40,0:11:23.37,Default,,0,0,0,,of the Roman Empire.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.37,0:11:26.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, 325 C.E., that looks right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.70,0:11:29.71,Default,,0,0,0,,And Constantine, that looks right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.71,0:11:32.07,Default,,0,0,0,,But look at the word “official”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.07,0:11:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,—“official religion.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.28,0:11:38.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Constantine never established Christianity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.31,0:11:41.58,Default,,0,0,0,,as the official religion \Nof the Roman Empire. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.58,0:11:45.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In 313 B.C.E., \Nhe did make it legal to be a Christian, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.35,0:11:48.26,Default,,0,0,0,,but paganism was still \None of the official religions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:48.26,0:11:52.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Apostate Christianity \Ndidn’t become the official religion \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.23,0:11:55.53,Default,,0,0,0,,until 391 C.E.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.53,0:11:57.53,Default,,0,0,0,,This one is tricky. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.53,0:11:59.90,Default,,0,0,0,,See how you do with this one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.90,0:12:01.90,Default,,0,0,0,,“Imagine the apostle Paul \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.90,0:12:04.71,Default,,0,0,0,,“during his first imprisonment in Rome, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.71,0:12:06.98,Default,,0,0,0,,“writing his letter to the Colossians \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.98,0:12:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,from a dark prison cell.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.65,0:12:12.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, if you look in the back \Nof the New World Translation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.95,0:12:16.62,Default,,0,0,0,,you’ll find that Paul did write his letter \Nto the Colossians while in Rome, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.62,0:12:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and he was imprisoned at the time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.22,0:12:22.59,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what’s the problem? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.59,0:12:24.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“Dark prison cell.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.89,0:12:27.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Where was Paul \Nduring his first imprisonment? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.73,0:12:30.37,Default,,0,0,0,,In his own rented house. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.37,0:12:32.64,Default,,0,0,0,,So the statement “dark prison cell,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.64,0:12:36.74,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s very dramatic, but it’s all wrong.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.74,0:12:39.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s an old one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.31,0:12:41.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“While Paul generally preached \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.31,0:12:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“to people of the nations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.31,0:12:45.38,Default,,0,0,0,,“Peter was sent to the Jews. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.38,0:12:47.95,Default,,0,0,0,,“Contrary to popular belief, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.95,0:12:50.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Peter was never in Rome.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.85,0:12:53.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Some scholars used to make that statement, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.52,0:12:55.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and they made it 60 years ago: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.69,0:12:58.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“Peter was never in Rome.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.59,0:13:00.60,Default,,0,0,0,,But can we really say that? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.60,0:13:02.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we be that dogmatic? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.80,0:13:05.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we say that he didn’t even spend \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.37,0:13:07.67,Default,,0,0,0,,vacation time or have a short visit in Rome? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.67,0:13:09.71,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we cannot. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.71,0:13:11.77,Default,,0,0,0,,So it would be more accurate to state: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.77,0:13:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“There is no record \Nthat Peter ever lived in Rome.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.11,0:13:18.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.91,0:13:21.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“We can have confidence in the Bible\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.62,0:13:25.12,Default,,0,0,0,,—it is mankind’s oldest book.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.12,0:13:28.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“Mankind’s oldest book.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.96,0:13:31.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Years ago, some scholars believed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.73,0:13:35.36,Default,,0,0,0,,that texts written \Nby Adam, Noah, and others \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.36,0:13:37.83,Default,,0,0,0,,survived the Flood \Nand became part of the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.83,0:13:39.84,Default,,0,0,0,,And if that were true, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.84,0:13:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,then we could say that the Bible \Nis mankind’s oldest book. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.47,0:13:46.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, here’s a quote \Nfrom Insight on the Scriptures, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.71,0:13:48.74,Default,,0,0,0,,our Bible encyclopedia. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.74,0:13:53.05,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: \N“There is no way to establish definitely \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.05,0:13:55.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“that some of the histories \Nmentioned in the book of Genesis \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.85,0:13:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,were committed to writing \Nbefore the Flood.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.12,0:14:03.39,Default,,0,0,0,,So, today we might call the Bible \None of mankind’s oldest books \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.39,0:14:06.90,Default,,0,0,0,,or the world’s oldest modern book, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.90,0:14:09.43,Default,,0,0,0,,as we do in one of our videos.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.43,0:14:11.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s the last one: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.53,0:14:13.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“In 1517, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.74,0:14:17.17,Default,,0,0,0,,“Martin Luther nailed his 95 theses \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.17,0:14:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,on the door of a church \Nin Wittenberg, Germany.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.21,0:14:24.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we’ve highlighted “95,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.38,0:14:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,but there are questions \Nabout the entire statement. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.32,0:14:29.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Some modern scholars have done \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.95,0:14:32.96,Default,,0,0,0,,a tremendous, exhaustive study \Nof the life of Martin Luther, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.96,0:14:35.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and they claim \Nthat he couldn’t have compiled \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.66,0:14:40.33,Default,,0,0,0,,all 95 of his theses by 1517. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.33,0:14:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Others go so far as to claim \Nthat it never happened\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.10,0:14:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—that he never did nail his theses \Non the door of the church. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.00,0:14:51.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Still others are just as adamant \Nthat it’s all true\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.41,0:14:53.44,Default,,0,0,0,,—that it all happened. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.44,0:14:55.71,Default,,0,0,0,,So there’s no consensus. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.71,0:14:58.18,Default,,0,0,0,,We would have to modify the statement\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.18,0:15:01.05,Default,,0,0,0,,—“some believe” or “it is believed”—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.05,0:15:03.05,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to make it more accurate \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.05,0:15:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and to acknowledge the fact \Nthat there are differences of opinion.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.36,0:15:11.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how did you do on the quiz? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.26,0:15:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If you’re like me, you’ve probably made \Nsome of those statements yourself at times. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.00,0:15:19.84,Default,,0,0,0,,The statements were based \Non the best research we had at the time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.84,0:15:23.27,Default,,0,0,0,,But this is to illustrate \Nthe fact that times change; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.27,0:15:26.28,Default,,0,0,0,,research facilities improve. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.28,0:15:30.95,Default,,0,0,0,,A scholar does exhaustive research \Non one point of history, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.95,0:15:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,and he uncovers things \Nthat were previously unknown. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.25,0:15:36.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So we have to keep up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.25,0:15:38.72,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to check, check, check. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.72,0:15:42.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And when credible research \Nreveals that we have to adjust \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.86,0:15:45.49,Default,,0,0,0,,or tweak a statement \Nthat we made in the past, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.49,0:15:48.03,Default,,0,0,0,,we do so without hesitation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.03,0:15:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Our goal is to provide information \Nthat is as accurate as possible \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.04,0:15:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,because we know that you \Nbrothers and sisters use this information. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:56.37,0:15:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,You quote it in the field ministry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.37,0:16:00.44,Default,,0,0,0,,You use it in your public talks. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.44,0:16:02.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So we want to make sure \Nthat our brothers are fed \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.98,0:16:07.12,Default,,0,0,0,,with the most accurate \Nspiritual food possible.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.12,0:16:10.82,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re imperfect, of course, \Nand we are going to make mistakes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.82,0:16:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,And when we do, \Nwe have to correct them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.59,0:16:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Our goal is to do the best we can \Nin all our imperfection.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.83,0:16:22.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, how does it make you feel? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.16,0:16:24.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I know how it makes me feel. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.67,0:16:29.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m grateful that Jehovah’s organization \Ntakes accuracy so seriously. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.67,0:16:31.87,Default,,0,0,0,,It gives me confidence. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.87,0:16:35.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And, you know, I’m reminded \Nof the description of another researcher, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.74,0:16:42.28,Default,,0,0,0,,as recorded at Ecclesiastes 12:9, 10. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.28,0:16:44.29,Default,,0,0,0,,You know who this is. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.29,0:16:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Ecclesiastes 12:9, 10: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.72,0:16:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“Not only had the congregator become wise \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.36,0:16:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,“but he continually taught \Nthe people what he knew, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.23,0:16:58.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he pondered \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.57,0:17:01.90,Default,,0,0,0,,“and made a thorough search \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.90,0:17:04.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“in order to compile many proverbs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.87,0:17:07.74,Default,,0,0,0,,“The congregator sought \Nto find delightful words \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.74,0:17:10.43,Default,,0,0,0,,and to record accurate words of truth.”\N
